{
  "texts": [
    "Research synthesis in the form of meta-analysis has a dramatic impact on the development of cumulative knowledge in psychology and other disciplines (DeGeest & Schmidt, 2011).",
    "As such, meta-analysis has been acknowledged as one of the most important methodological developments in behavioral and other sciences (Cooper et al., 2010; Egger et al., 2001).",
    "Most conventional methods for meta-analysis hold the assumption that the synthesis is based on effect sizes that are not related to each other (e.g., Cheung, 2014; Rosenthal, 1984).",
    "However, primary studies often report multiple effect sizes that are eligible for inclusion given the scope of a meta-analysis, implying that effect sizes are related to each other.",
    "This effect size dependency -also referred to as effect size interrelatedness or interdependency -may occur, for instance because separate experiments were conducted in a primary study, a primary study used multiple methods (e.g., self-report, interviews) for assessing the same construct, or the same participants were examined over multiple timepoints."
  ]
}